<DOC><DOCNO> AP900602-0190 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-90 0044EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-OSHA-Thrall     06-02 0169</FIRST><SECOND>AM-OSHA-Thrall,0178</SECOND><HEAD>OSHA Proposes Fines Against Illinois Firm</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government on Friday proposed fines of morethan $610,000 for an Illinois railroad car manufacturer thatallegedly violated workplace safety laws.   Thrall Car Manufacturing Co. was accused of 141 violations of theOccupational Safety and Health Administration's noise, welding fumeand respirator regulations.   Craig Dowden, a spokesman at Thrall, based in Chicago Heights,Ill., said most of the alleged violations involved testingrequirements that have been implemented.   ``Thrall Car has a history of concern for the safety of itsemployees and will be discussing these alleged violations withOSHA,'' Dowden said.   The alleged violations involved a Chicago Heights plant thatemploys 500 workers, the agency said. An investigation began inDecember 1989 after employees complained of excessive exposure tochemicals at the plant.   The firm, with another two plants in Illinois and two in Georgia,employs a total of 2,400 workers.   The company will have a chance to argue against the fines beforethey become final.</TEXT></DOC>